# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: multi-agent-systems-ai
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] An **agent-based model** (**ABM**) is a computational model for simulating the actions and interactions of an autonomous agent (both individual or collective entities such as organizations or groups) to understand the behavior of a system and what governs its outcomes.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] It combines elements of game theory, complex systems, emergence, computational sociology, multi-agent systems, and evolutionary programming.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Monte Carlo methods are used to understand the stochasticity of these models.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Particularly within ecology, an ABM is also called an **individual-based model** (**IBM**).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] A review of literature on individual-based models, agent-based models, and multiagent systems shows that ABMs are used in many scientific domains including biology, ecology, and social science.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-based modeling is related to, but distinct from, the concept of a **multi-agent system** .
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] An agent-based model is a type of microscale model that simulates the simultaneous operations and interactions of multiple agents in an attempt to re-create and predict the appearance of complex phenomena.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The process is one of emergence, which some express as "the whole is greater than the sum of its parts".
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In other words, higher-level system properties emerge from the interactions of lower-level subsystems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Or, macro-scale state changes emerge from micro-scale agent behaviors.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Or, simple behaviors (meaning rules followed by agents) generate complex behaviors (meaning state changes at the whole system level).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] An individual agent is typically characterized as boundedly rational, presumed to be acting in what it perceives as its their own interests, such as reproduction, economic benefit, or social status, using heuristics or simple decision-making rules.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] An ABM agent may experience "learning", adaptation, and reproduction.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] An agent-based model is usually composed of (1) numerous agents specified at various scales (typically referred to as agent-granularity), (2) decision-making heuristics, (3) learning rules or adaptive processes,(4) an interaction topology, and (5) an environment.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] An ABM is typically implemented as a computer simulation, either as custom software or using an ABM toolkit.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] This software can be then used to test how changes in individual behavior will affect the system's overall behavior.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The idea of agent-based modeling was developed as a relatively simple concept in the late 1940s.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Since it requires computation-intensive procedures, it did not become widespread until the 1990s.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The history of the agent-based model can be traced back to the Von Neumann machine, a theoretical machine capable of reproduction.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The device von Neumann proposed would follow precisely detailed instructions to fashion a copy of itself.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The concept was then built upon by von Neumann's friend Stanislaw Ulam, also a mathematician; Ulam suggested that the machine be built on paper, as a collection of cells on a grid.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The idea intrigued von Neumann, who drew it up — creating the first of the devices later termed cellular automata.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Oliver Selfridge's 1958 Pandemonium - A Paradigm for Learning paper was an important early theorectical contribution in establishing agent orientated architecture, though it used the term metaphorical 'demon' instead of agent.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Carl Hewitt 1973 Actor model contained one of the earliest uses of agents as active entities rather than passive structures.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Another advance was introduced by the mathematician John Conway.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] He constructed the well-known Game of Life.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Unlike von Neumann's machine, the Game of Life operated by simple rules in a virtual world in the form of a 2-dimensional checkerboard.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The Simula programming language, developed in the mid-1960s and widely implemented by the early 1970s, was the first framework for automating step-by-step agent simulations.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] One of the earliest agent-based models in concept was Thomas Schelling's segregation model, which was discussed in his paper "Dynamic Models of Segregation" in 1971.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Though Schelling originally used coins and graph paper rather than computers, his models embodied the basic concept of agent-based models as autonomous agents interacting in a shared environment with an observed aggregate, emergent outcome.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In the late 1970s, Paulien Hogeweg and Bruce Hesper began experimenting with individual models of ecology.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] One of their first results was to show that the social structure of bumble-bee colonies emerged as a result of simple rules that govern the behaviour of individual bees.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] They introduced the ToDo principle, referring to the way agents "do what there is to do" at any given time.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In the early 1980s, Robert Axelrod hosted a tournament of Prisoner's Dilemma strategies and had them interact in an agent-based manner to determine a winner.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Axelrod would go on to develop many other agent-based models in the field of political science that examine phenomena from ethnocentrism to the dissemination of culture.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] By the late 1980s, Craig Reynolds' work on flocking models contributed to the development of some of the first biological agent-based models that contained social characteristics.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] He tried to model the reality of lively biological agents, known as artificial life, a term coined by Christopher Langton.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] At the same time, during the 1980s, social scientists, mathematicians, operations researchers, and a scattering of people from other disciplines developed Computational and Mathematical Organization Theory (CMOT).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] This field grew as a special interest group of The Institute of Management Sciences (TIMS) and its sister society, the Operations Research Society of America (ORSA).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The 1990s were especially notable for the expansion of ABM within the social sciences, one notable effort was the large-scale ABM, Sugarscape, developed by Joshua M.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Epstein and Robert Axtell to simulate and explore the role of social phenomena such as seasonal migrations, pollution, sexual reproduction, combat, and transmission of disease and even culture.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Other notable 1990s developments included Carnegie Mellon University's Kathleen Carley ABM, to explore the co-evolution of social networks and culture.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The Santa Fe Institute (SFI) was important in encouraging the development of the ABM modeling platform Swarm under the leadership of Christopher Langton.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Research conducted through SFI allowed the expansion of ABM techniques to a number of fields including study of the social and spatial dynamics of small-scale human societies and primates.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] During this 1990s timeframe Nigel Gilbert published the first textbook on Social Simulation: Simulation for the social scientist (1999) and established a journal from the perspective of social sciences: the *Journal of Artificial Societies and Social Simulation* (JASSS).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Other than JASSS, agent-based models of any discipline are within scope of SpringerOpen journal *Complex Adaptive Systems Modeling* (CASM).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Through the mid-1990s, the social sciences thread of ABM began to focus on such issues as designing effective teams, understanding the communication required for organizational effectiveness, and the behavior of social networks.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] CMOT—later renamed Computational Analysis of Social and Organizational Systems (CASOS)—incorporated more and more agent-based modeling.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Samuelson (2000) is a good brief overview of the early history, and Samuelson (2005) and Samuelson and Macal (2006) trace the more recent developments.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In the late 1990s, the merger of TIMS and ORSA to form INFORMS, and the move by INFORMS from two meetings each year to one, helped to spur the CMOT group to form a separate society, the North American Association for Computational Social and Organizational Sciences (NAACSOS).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Kathleen Carley was a major contributor, especially to models of social networks, obtaining National Science Foundation funding for the annual conference and serving as the first president of NAACSOS.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] She was succeeded by David Sallach of the University of Chicago and Argonne National Laboratory, and then by Michael Prietula of Emory University.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] At about the same time NAACSOS began, the European Social Simulation Association (ESSA) and the Pacific Asian Association for Agent-Based Approach in Social Systems Science (PAAA), counterparts of NAACSOS, were organized.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] As of 2013, these three organizations collaborate internationally.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The First World Congress on Social Simulation was held under their joint sponsorship in Kyoto, Japan, in August 2006.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The Second World Congress was held in the northern Virginia suburbs of Washington, D.C., in July 2008, with George Mason University taking the lead role in local arrangements.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] More recently, Ron Sun developed methods for basing agent-based simulation on models of human cognition, known as cognitive social simulation.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Bill McKelvey, Suzanne Lohmann, Dario Nardi, Dwight Read and others at UCLA have also made significant contributions in organizational behavior and decision-making.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Since 1991, UCLA has arranged a conference at Lake Arrowhead, California, that has become another major gathering point for practitioners in this field.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] After the advent of large language models, researchers began applying interacting language models to agent based modeling.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In one widely cited paper, agentic language models interacted in a sandbox environment to perform activities like planning birthday parties and holding elections.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Most computational modeling research describes systems in equilibrium or as moving between equilibria.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-based modeling, however, using simple rules, can result in different sorts of complex and interesting behavior.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The three ideas central to agent-based models are agents as objects, emergence, and complexity.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-based models consist of dynamically interacting rule-based agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The systems within which they interact can create real-world-like complexity.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Typically agents are situated in space and time and reside in networks or in lattice-like neighborhoods.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The location of the agents and their responsive behavior are encoded in algorithmic form in computer programs.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In some cases, though not always, the agents may be considered as intelligent and purposeful.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In ecological ABM (often referred to as "individual-based models" in ecology), agents may, for example, be trees in a forest, and would not be considered intelligent, although they may be "purposeful" in the sense of optimizing access to a resource (such as water).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The modeling process is best described as inductive.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The modeler makes those assumptions thought most relevant to the situation at hand and then watches phenomena emerge from the agents' interactions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Sometimes that result is an equilibrium.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Sometimes, however, it is an unintelligible mangle.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In some ways, agent-based models complement traditional analytic methods.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Where analytic methods enable humans to characterize the equilibria of a system, agent-based models allow the possibility of generating those equilibria.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] This generative contribution may be the most mainstream of the potential benefits of agent-based modeling.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-based models can explain the emergence of higher-order patterns—network structures of terrorist organizations and the Internet, power-law distributions in the sizes of traffic jams, wars, and stock-market crashes, and social segregation that persists despite populations of tolerant people.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-based models also can be used to identify lever points, defined as moments in time in which interventions have extreme consequences, and to distinguish among types of path dependency.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Rather than focusing on stable states, many models consider a system's robustness—the ways that complex systems adapt to internal and external pressures so as to maintain their functionalities.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The task of harnessing that complexity requires consideration of the agents themselves—their diversity, connectedness, and level of interactions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Exploratory Agent-based Modeling Level for developing agent-based models for assessing the feasibility of further research.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] This can e.g. be useful for developing proof-of-concept models such as for funding applications without requiring an extensive learning curve for the researchers.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Descriptive Agent-based Modeling (DREAM) for developing descriptions of agent-based models by means of using templates and complex network-based models.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Building DREAM models allows model comparison across scientific disciplines.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Validated agent-based modeling using Virtual Overlay Multiagent system (VOMAS) for the development of verified and validated models in a formal manner.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Other methods of describing agent-based models include code templates and text-based methods such as the ODD (Overview, Design concepts, and Design Details) protocol.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The role of the environment where agents live, both macro and micro, is also becoming an important factor in agent-based modelling and simulation work.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Simple environment affords simple agents, but complex environments generate diversity of behavior.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] One strength of agent-based modelling is its ability to mediate information flow between scales.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] When additional details about an agent are needed, a researcher can integrate it with models describing the extra details.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] When one is interested in the emergent behaviours demonstrated by the agent population, they can combine the agent-based model with a continuum model describing population dynamics.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In the resulting modular model, signal transduction and gene regulation are described by a logical model, metabolism by constraint-based models, cell population dynamics are described by an agent-based model, and systemic cytokine concentrations by ordinary differential equations.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In this multi-scale model, the agent-based model occupies the central place and orchestrates every stream of information flow between scales.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have also been used for developing decision support systems such as for breast cancer.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-based models are increasingly being used to model pharmacological systems in early stage and pre-clinical research to aid in drug development and gain insights into biological systems that would not be possible *a priori*.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Military applications have also been evaluated.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Moreover, agent-based models have been recently employed to study molecular-level biological systems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have also been written to describe ecological processes at work in ancient systems, such as those in dinosaur environments and more recent ancient systems as well.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-based models now complement traditional compartmental models, the usual type of epidemiological models.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] ABMs have been shown to be superior to compartmental models in regard to the accuracy of predictions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Recently, ABMs such as CovidSim by epidemiologist Neil Ferguson, have been used to inform public health (nonpharmaceutical) interventions against the spread of SARS-CoV-2.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Epidemiological ABMs have been criticized for simplifying and unrealistic assumptions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Still, they can be useful in informing decisions regarding mitigation and suppression measures in cases when ABMs are accurately calibrated.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The ABMs for such simulations are mostly based on synthetic populations, since the data of the actual population is not always available.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have been used since the mid-1990s to solve a variety of business and technology problems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Examples of applications include marketing, organizational behaviour and cognition, team working, supply chain optimization and logistics, modeling of consumer behavior, including word of mouth, social network effects, distributed computing, workforce management, and portfolio management.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] They have also been used to analyze traffic congestion.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Recently, agent based modelling and simulation has been applied to various domains such as studying the impact of publication venues by researchers in the computer science domain (journals versus conferences).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In addition, ABMs have been used to simulate information delivery in ambient assisted environments.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] A November 2016 article in arXiv analyzed an agent based simulation of posts spread in Facebook.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In the domain of peer-to-peer, ad hoc and other self-organizing and complex networks, the usefulness of agent based modeling and simulation has been shown.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The use of a computer science-based formal specification framework coupled with wireless sensor networks and an agent-based simulation has recently been demonstrated.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent based evolutionary search or algorithm is a new research topic for solving complex optimization problems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] In the realm of team science, agent-based modeling has been utilized to assess the effects of team members' characteristics and biases on team performance across various settings.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] By simulating interactions between agents—each representing individual team members with distinct traits and biases—this modeling approach enables researchers to explore how these factors collectively influence the dynamics and outcomes of team performance.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Consequently, agent-based modeling provides a nuanced understanding of team science, facilitating a deeper exploration of the subtleties and variabilities inherent in team-based collaborations.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Prior to, and during the 2008 financial crisis, interest has grown in ABMs as possible tools for economic analysis.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] ABMs do not assume the economy can achieve equilibrium and "representative agents" are replaced by agents with diverse, dynamic, and interdependent behavior including herding.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] ABMs take a "bottom-up" approach and can generate extremely complex and volatile simulated economies.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] ABMs can represent unstable systems with crashes and booms that develop out of non-linear (disproportionate) responses to proportionally small changes.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] A July 2010 article in *The Economist* looked at ABMs as alternatives to DSGE models.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The journal *Nature* also encouraged agent-based modeling with an editorial that suggested ABMs can do a better job of representing financial markets and other economic complexities than standard models along with an essay by J.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Doyne Farmer and Duncan Foley that argued ABMs could fulfill both the desires of Keynes to represent a complex economy and of Robert Lucas to construct models based on microfoundations.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Farmer and Foley pointed to progress that has been made using ABMs to model parts of an economy, but argued for the creation of a very large model that incorporates low level models.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] By modeling a complex system of analysts based on three distinct behavioral profiles – imitating, anti-imitating, and indifferent – financial markets were simulated to high accuracy.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Results showed a correlation between network morphology and the stock market index.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] However, the ABM approach has been criticized for its lack of robustness between models, where similar models can yield very different results.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] ABMs have been deployed in architecture and urban planning to evaluate design and to simulate pedestrian flow in the urban environment and the examination of public policy applications to land-use.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] There is also a growing field of socio-economic analysis of infrastructure investment impact using ABM's ability to discern systemic impacts upon a socio-economic network.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Heterogeneity and dynamics can be easily built in ABM models to address wealth inequality and social mobility.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] ABMs have also been proposed as applied educational tools for diplomats in the field of international relations and for domestic and international policymakers to enhance their evaluation of public policy.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] ABMs have also been applied in water resources planning and management, particularly for exploring, simulating, and predicting the performance of infrastructure design and policy decisions, and in assessing the value of cooperation and information exchange in large water resources systems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agents for Systems are divided in two subcategories.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-supported systems deal with the use of agents as a support facility to enable computer assistance in problem solving or enhancing cognitive capabilities.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Agent-based systems focus on the use of agents for the generation of model behavior in a system evaluation (system studies and analyses).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Hallerbach et al. discussed the application of agent-based approaches for the development and validation of automated driving systems via a digital twin of the vehicle-under-test and microscopic traffic simulation based on independent agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Waymo has created a multi-agent simulation environment Carcraft to test algorithms for self-driving cars.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] It simulates traffic interactions between human drivers, pedestrians and automated vehicles.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] People's behavior is imitated by artificial agents based on data of real human behavior.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The basic idea of using agent-based modeling to understand self-driving cars was discussed as early as 2003.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Many ABM frameworks are designed for serial von-Neumann computer architectures, limiting the speed and scalability of implemented models.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Since emergent behavior in large-scale ABMs is dependent of population size, scalability restrictions may hinder model validation.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Such limitations have mainly been addressed using distributed computing, with frameworks such as Repast HPC specifically dedicated to these types of implementations.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] While such approaches map well to cluster and supercomputer architectures, issues related to communication and synchronization, as well as deployment complexity, remain potential obstacles for their widespread adoption.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] A recent development is the use of data-parallel algorithms on Graphics Processing Units GPUs for ABM simulation.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] The extreme memory bandwidth combined with the sheer number crunching power of multi-processor GPUs has enabled simulation of millions of agents at tens of frames per second.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Since Agent-Based Modeling is more of a modeling framework than a particular piece of software or platform, it has often been used in conjunction with other modeling forms.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] For instance, agent-based models have also been combined with Geographic Information Systems (GIS).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] This provides a useful combination where the ABM serves as a process model and the GIS system can provide a model of pattern.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Similarly, Social Network Analysis (SNA) tools and agent-based models are sometimes integrated, where the ABM is used to simulate the dynamics on the network while the SNA tool models and analyzes the network of interactions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Tools like GAMA provide a natural way to integrate system dynamics and GIS with ABM.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Verification and validation (V&V) of simulation models is extremely important.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Verification involves making sure the implemented model matches the conceptual model, whereas validation ensures that the implemented model has some relationship to the real-world.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Face validation, sensitivity analysis, calibration, and statistical validation are different aspects of validation.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] A discrete-event simulation framework approach for the validation of agent-based systems has been proposed.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] A comprehensive resource on empirical validation of agent-based models can be found here.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] As an example of V&V technique, consider VOMAS (virtual overlay multi-agent system), a software engineering based approach, where a virtual overlay multi-agent system is developed alongside the agent-based model.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Muazi et al. also provide an example of using VOMAS for verification and validation of a forest fire simulation model.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Another software engineering method, i.e.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] Test-Driven Development has been adapted to for agent-based model validation.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/agent-based-model] This approach has another advantage that allows an automatic validation using unit test tools.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] A **blackboard system** is an artificial intelligence approach based on the blackboard architectural model, where a common knowledge base, the "blackboard", is iteratively updated by a diverse group of specialist knowledge sources, starting with a problem specification and ending with a solution.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Each knowledge source updates the blackboard with a partial solution when its internal constraints match the blackboard state.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] In this way, the specialists work together to solve the problem.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] The blackboard model was originally designed as a way to handle complex, ill-defined problems, where the solution is the sum of its parts.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] The **blackboard**, a shared repository of problems, partial solutions, suggestions, and contributed information.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] The blackboard can be thought of as a dynamic "library" of contributions to the current problem that have been recently "published" by other knowledge sources.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] The **control shell**, which controls the flow of problem-solving activity in the system.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Just as the eager human specialists need a moderator to prevent them from trampling each other in a mad dash to grab the chalk, KSs need a mechanism to organize their use in the most effective and coherent fashion.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] In a blackboard system, this is provided by the control shell.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] A blackboard system is the central space in a multi-agent system.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] It's used for describing the world as a communication platform for agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] To realize a blackboard in a computer program, a machine readable notation is needed in which facts can be stored.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] One attempt in doing so is a SQL database, another option is the **Learnable Task Modeling Language (LTML)**.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] The syntax of the LTML planning language is similar to PDDL, but adds extra features like control structures and OWL-S models.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] LTML was developed in 2007 as part of a much larger project called POIROT (Plan Order Induction by Reasoning from One Trial), which is a Learning from demonstrations framework for process mining.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] In POIROT, Plan traces and hypotheses are stored in the LTML syntax for creating semantic web services.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Here is a small example: A human user is executing a workflow in a computer game.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] The user presses some buttons and interacts with the game engine.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] While the user interacts with the game, a plan trace is created.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] That means the user's actions are stored in a logfile.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] The logfile gets transformed into a machine readable notation which is enriched by semantic attributes.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] The result is a textfile in the LTML syntax which is put on the blackboard.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Agents (software programs in the blackboard system) are able to parse the LTML syntax.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] We start by discussing two well known early blackboard systems, BB1 and GBB, below and then discuss more recent implementations and applications.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] The BB1 blackboard architecture was originally inspired by studies of how humans plan to perform multiple tasks in a trip, used task-planning as a simplified example of tactical planning for the Office of Naval Research.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] A key innovation of BB1 was that it applied this opportunistic planning model to its own control, using the same blackboard model of incremental, opportunistic, problem-solving that was applied to solve domain problems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Meta-level reasoning with control knowledge sources could then monitor whether planning and problem-solving were proceeding as expected or stalled.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] If stalled, BB1 could switch from one strategy to another as conditions – such as the goals being considered or the time remaining – changed.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] BB1 was applied in multiple domains: construction site planning, inferring 3-D protein structures from X-ray crystallography, intelligent tutoring systems, and real-time patient monitoring.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] BB1 also allowed domain-general language frameworks to be designed for wide classes of problems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] For example, the ACCORD language framework defined a particular approach to solving configuration problems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] The problem-solving approach was to incrementally assemble a solution by adding objects and constraints, one at a time.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Actions in the ACCORD language framework appear as short English-like commands or sentences for specifying preferred actions, events to trigger KSes, preconditions to run a KS action, and obviation conditions to discard a KS action that is no longer relevant.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] GBB focused on efficiency, in contrast to BB1, which focused more on sophisticated reasoning and opportunistic planning.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] GBB improves efficiency by allowing blackboards to be multi-dimensional, where dimensions can be either ordered or not, and then by increasing the efficiency of pattern matching.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] GBB1, one of GBB's control shells implements BB1's style of control while adding efficiency improvements.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Other well-known of early academic blackboard systems are the Hearsay II speech recognition system and Douglas Hofstadter's Copycat and Numbo projects.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Blackboard systems are used routinely in many military C4ISTAR systems for detecting and tracking objects.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Another example of current use is in Game AI, where they are considered a standard AI tool to help with adding AI to video games.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Blackboard-like systems have been constructed within modern Bayesian machine learning settings, using agents to add and remove Bayesian network nodes.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] In these 'Bayesian Blackboard' systems, the heuristics can acquire more rigorous probabilistic meanings as proposal and acceptances in Metropolis Hastings sampling though the space of possible structures.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Conversely, using these mappings, existing Metropolis-Hastings samplers over structural spaces may now thus be viewed as forms of blackboard systems even when not named as such by the authors.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Such samplers are commonly found in musical transcription algorithms for example.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/blackboard-system] Blackboard systems have also been used to build large-scale intelligent systems for the annotation of media content, automating parts of traditional social science research.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] A **multi-agent system** (**MAS**) or "self-organized system" is a computational system composed of multiple interacting intelligent agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Multi-agent systems can solve problems that are difficult or impossible for an individual agent or a monolithic system to solve.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Intelligence may include methodic, functional, procedural approaches, algorithmic search or reinforcement learning.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] With advancements in large language models (LLMs), LLM-based multi-agent systems have emerged as a new area of research, enabling more sophisticated interactions and coordination among agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Despite considerable overlap, a multi-agent system is not always the same as an agent-based model (ABM).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] The goal of an ABM is to search for explanatory insight into the collective behavior of agents (which do not necessarily need to be "intelligent") obeying simple rules, typically in natural systems, rather than in solving specific practical or engineering problems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] The terminology of ABM tends to be used more often in the science, and MAS in engineering and technology.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Applications where multi-agent systems research may deliver an appropriate approach include online trading, disaster response, target surveillance and social structure modelling.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Multi-agent systems consist of agents and their environment.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Typically, research on multi-agent systems refers to software agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] However, the agents in a multi-agent system could equally well be robots, humans, or human teams, and may consist of combined human-agent teams.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Agents can be divided into types spanning simple to complex.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Agent actions are typically mediated via an appropriate middleware.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] This middleware offers a first-class design abstraction for multi-agent systems, providing means to govern resource access and agent coordination.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Multi-agent systems can manifest self-organisation as well as self-direction and other control paradigms and related complex behaviors even when the individual strategies of all their agents are simple.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] When agents can share knowledge using any agreed language, within the constraints of the system's communication protocol, the approach may lead to a common improvement.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Example languages are Knowledge Query Manipulation Language (KQML) or Agent Communication Language (ACL).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Decision protocols in multi-agent systems refer to the structured rules and procedures that agents follow to reach collective decisions or agreements.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Such protocols specify how agents share information, negotiate, and resolve conflicts, ensuring coordinated behavior and effective joint actions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Decision protocols can range from voting mechanisms to consensus-building algorithms, and they significantly influence the efficiency and reliability of multi-agent interactions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Many MAS are implemented in computer simulations, stepping the system through discrete "time steps".
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] The MAS components communicate typically using a weighted request matrix, e.g.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] also considering other components, evolving "contracts" and the restriction sets of the component algorithms.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Another paradigm commonly used with MAS is the "pheromone", where components leave information for other nearby components.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] These pheromones may evaporate/concentrate with time, that is their values may decrease (or increase).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] MAS tend to find the best solution for their problems without intervention.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] There is high similarity here to physical phenomena, such as energy minimizing, where physical objects tend to reach the lowest energy possible within the physically constrained world.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] For example: many of the cars entering a metropolis in the morning will be available for leaving that same metropolis in the evening.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] The systems also tend to prevent propagation of faults, self-recover and be fault tolerant, mainly due to the redundancy of components.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] A MAS involves more than just the design of an intelligent system.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] It also provides insights and understanding about interactions among humans, as they organize themselves into various groups, committees, societies, and economies in order to improve their lives.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] For example, economists have been studying multiple agents for more than two hundred years, ever since Adam Smith in the eighteenth century, with the goal of being able to understand and predict economies.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Economics provides ways to characterize masses of agents. and these are useful for DAI.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] But in return, DAI provides a means to construct artificial economies that can test economists’ theories before, rather than after, they are applied.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Frameworks have emerged that implement common standards (such as the FIPA and OMG MASIF standards).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] JADE, save time and aid in the standardization of MAS development.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Currently though, no standard is actively maintained from FIPA or OMG.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Efforts for further development of software agents in industrial context are carried out in IEEE IES technical committee on Industrial Agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] With advancements in large language models (LLMs) such as ChatGPT, LLM-based multi-agent frameworks, such as CAMEL, have emerged as a new paradigm for developing multi-agent applications.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Recent work has shown that such debate-oriented systems vary in their orchestration (e.g., discussion paradigms).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] The MALLM framework is used to systematically evaluate possible configurations of frameworks.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] MAS have not only been applied in academic research, but also in industry.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] MAS are applied in the real world to graphical applications such as computer games.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] It is widely advocated for use in networking and mobile technologies, to achieve automatic and dynamic load balancing, high scalability and self-healing networks.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] They are being used for coordinated defence systems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Other applications include transportation, logistics, graphics, manufacturing, power system, smartgrids, and the GIS.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Also, Multi-agent Systems Artificial Intelligence (MAAI) are used for simulating societies, the purpose thereof being helpful in the fields of climate, energy, epidemiology, conflict management, child abuse, ....
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Some organisations working on using multi-agent system models include Center for Modelling Social Systems, Centre for Research in Social Simulation, Centre for Policy Modelling, Society for Modelling and Simulation International.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/multi-agent-system] Vehicular traffic with controlled autonomous vehicles can be modelling as a multi-agent system involving crowd dynamics.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] In computer science, a **software agent** is a computer program that acts for a user or another program in a relationship of agency.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The term *agent* is derived from the Latin *agere* (to do): an agreement to act on one's behalf.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Such "action on behalf of" implies the authority to decide which, if any, action is appropriate.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Some agents are colloquially known as *bots*, from *robot*.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] They may be embodied, as when execution is paired with a robot body, or as software such as a chatbot executing on a computer, such as a mobile device, e.g.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Software agents may be autonomous or work together with other agents or people.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Software agents interacting with people (e.g. chatbots, human-robot interaction environments) may possess human-like qualities such as natural language understanding and speech, personality or embody humanoid form (see Asimo).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The concept of an agent provides a method of describing a complex software entity that is capable of acting with a certain degree of autonomy in order to accomplish tasks on behalf of its host.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] But unlike objects, which are defined in terms of *methods* and *attributes*, an agent is defined in terms of its behavior.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] All agents are programs, but not all programs are agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Contrasting the term with related concepts may help clarify its meaning.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Franklin & Graesser (1997) discuss four key notions that distinguish agents from arbitrary programs: reaction to the environment, autonomy, goal-orientation and persistence.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Software agents may offer various benefits to their end users by automating complex or repetitive tasks.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] However, there are organizational and cultural impacts of this technology that need to be considered prior to implementing software agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] People like to perform easy tasks providing the sensation of success unless the repetition of the simple tasking is affecting the overall output.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] In general implementing software agents to perform administrative requirements provides a substantial increase in work contentment, as administering their own work does never please the worker.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The effort freed up serves for a higher degree of engagement in the substantial tasks of individual work.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Hence, software agents may provide the basics to implement self-controlled work, relieved from hierarchical controls and interference.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Such conditions may be secured by application of software agents for required formal support.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The cultural effects of the implementation of software agents include trust affliction, skills erosion, privacy attrition and social detachment.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Some users may not feel entirely comfortable fully delegating important tasks to software applications.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Those who start relying solely on intelligent agents may lose important skills, for example, relating to information literacy.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] In order to act on a user's behalf, a software agent needs to have a complete understanding of a user's profile, including his/her personal preferences.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] This, in turn, may lead to unpredictable privacy issues.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] When users start relying on their software agents more, especially for communication activities, they may lose contact with other human users and look at the world with the eyes of their agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] These consequences are what agent researchers and users must consider when dealing with intelligent agent technologies.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] To be more academic, software agent systems are a direct evolution of Multi-Agent Systems (MAS).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] MAS evolved from Distributed Artificial Intelligence (DAI), Distributed Problem Solving (DPS) and Parallel AI (PAI), thus inheriting all characteristics (good and bad) from DAI and AI.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] John Sculley's 1987 "Knowledge Navigator" video portrayed an image of a relationship between end-users and agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Being an ideal first, this field experienced a series of unsuccessful top-down implementations, instead of a piece-by-piece, bottom-up approach.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The range of agent types is now (from 1990) broad: WWW, search engines, etc.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Buyer agents travel around a network (e.g. the internet) retrieving information about goods and services.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] These agents, also known as 'shopping bots', work very efficiently for commodity products such as CDs, books, electronic components, and other one-size-fits-all products.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Buyer agents are typically optimized to allow for digital payment services used in e-commerce and traditional businesses.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] User agents, or personal agents, are intelligent agents that take action on your behalf.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Monitoring and surveillance agents are used to observe and report on equipment, usually computer systems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The agents may keep track of company inventory levels, observe competitors' prices and relay them back to the company, watch stock manipulation by insider trading and rumors, etc.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] For example, NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory has an agent that monitors inventory, planning, schedules equipment orders to keep costs down, and manages food storage facilities.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] These agents usually monitor complex computer networks that can keep track of the configuration of each computer connected to the network.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] A special case of monitoring-and-surveillance agents are organizations of agents used to automate decision-making process during tactical operations.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The agents monitor the status of assets (ammunition, weapons available, platforms for transport, etc.) and receive goals from higher level agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The agents then pursue the goals with the assets at hand, minimizing expenditure of the assets while maximizing goal attainment.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] This agent uses information technology to find trends and patterns in an abundance of information from many different sources.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The user can sort through this information in order to find whatever information they are seeking.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] A data mining agent operates in a data warehouse discovering information.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] A 'data warehouse' brings together information from many different sources.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] "Data mining" is the process of looking through the data warehouse to find information that you can use to take action, such as ways to increase sales or keep customers who are considering defecting.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] 'Classification' is one of the most common types of data mining, which finds patterns in information and categorizes them into different classes.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Data mining agents can also detect major shifts in trends or a key indicator and can detect the presence of new information and alert you to it.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] For example, the agent may detect a decline in the construction industry for an economy; based on this relayed information construction companies will be able to make intelligent decisions regarding the hiring/firing of employees or the purchase/lease of equipment in order to best suit their firm.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Some other examples of current intelligent agents include some spam filters, game bots, and server monitoring tools.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Search engine indexing bots also qualify as intelligent agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Software bots are becoming important in software engineering.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Agents are also used in software security application to intercept, examine and act on various types of content.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] For software agents to work together efficiently they must share semantics of their data elements.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] This can be done by having computer systems publish their metadata.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Agent systems are used to model real-world systems with concurrency or parallel processing.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The agent uses its access methods to go out into local and remote databases to forage for content.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] These access methods may include setting up news stream delivery to the agent, or retrieval from bulletin boards, or using a spider to walk the Web.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The content that is retrieved in this way is probably already partially filtered – by the selection of the newsfeed or the databases that are searched.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The agent next may use its detailed searching or language-processing machinery to extract keywords or signatures from the body of the content that has been received or retrieved.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] This abstracted content (or event) is then passed to the agent's Reasoning or inferencing machinery in order to decide what to do with the new content.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] This process combines the event content with the rule-based or knowledge content provided by the user.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] If this process finds a good hit or match in the new content, the agent may use another piece of its machinery to do a more detailed search on the content.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Finally, the agent may decide to take an action based on the new content; for example, to notify the user that an important event has occurred.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] This action is verified by a security function and then given the authority of the user.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The agent makes use of a user-access method to deliver that message to the user.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] If the user confirms that the event is important by acting quickly on the notification, the agent may also employ its learning machinery to increase its weighting for this kind of event.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Bots can act on behalf of their creators to do good as well as bad.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] There are a few ways which bots can be created to demonstrate that they are designed with the best intention and are not built to do harm.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] This is first done by having a bot identify itself in the user-agent HTTP header when communicating with a site.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] The source IP address must also be validated to establish itself as legitimate.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] Next, the bot must also always respect a site's robots.txt file since it has become the standard across most of the web.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/software-agent] And like respecting the robots.txt file, bots should shy away from being too aggressive and respect any crawl delay instructions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence systems consist typically of a population of simple agents or boids interacting locally with one another and with their environment.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The inspiration often comes from nature, especially biological systems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The agents follow very simple rules, and although there is no centralized control structure dictating how individual agents should behave, local, and to a certain degree random, interactions between such agents lead to the emergence of "intelligent" global behavior, unknown to the individual agents.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Examples of swarm intelligence in natural systems include ant colonies, bee colonies, bird flocking, hawks hunting, animal herding, bacterial growth, fish schooling and microbial intelligence.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The application of swarm principles to robots is called *swarm robotics* while *swarm intelligence* refers to the more general set of algorithms.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] *Swarm prediction* has been used in the context of forecasting problems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Similar approaches to those proposed for swarm robotics are considered for genetically modified organisms in synthetic collective intelligence.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Boids is an artificial life program, developed by Craig Reynolds in 1986, which simulates flocking.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] It was published in 1987 in the proceedings of the ACM SIGGRAPH conference.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The name "boid" corresponds to a shortened version of "bird-oid object", which refers to a bird-like object.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] As with most artificial life simulations, Boids is an example of emergent behavior; that is, the complexity of Boids arises from the interaction of individual agents (the boids, in this case) adhering to a set of simple rules.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] More complex rules can be added, such as obstacle avoidance and goal seeking.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Self-propelled particles (SPP), also referred to as the *Vicsek model*, was introduced in 1995 by Vicsek *et al.* as a special case of the boids model introduced in 1986 by Reynolds.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] A swarm is modelled in SPP by a collection of particles that move with a constant speed but respond to a random perturbation by adopting at each time increment the average direction of motion of the other particles in their local neighbourhood.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] SPP models predict that swarming animals share certain properties at the group level, regardless of the type of animals in the swarm.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Swarming systems give rise to emergent behaviours which occur at many different scales, some of which are turning out to be both universal and robust.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] It has become a challenge in theoretical physics to find minimal statistical models that capture these behaviours.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Social Potential Fields, developed in 1999 by John H.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Reif and Hongyan Wang , is one of the earliest models for Swarm Intelligence, developed for use for autonomous control of robot swarm systems that may consist of from hundreds to perhaps tens of thousands or more autonomous robots.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] It is the first paper to apply a potential field model to distributed autonomous multi-robot control.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] A Social Potential Field defines simple artificial force laws between pairs of robots or robot groups.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] These force laws are inverse-power force laws, incorporating both attraction and repulsion, similar but more general compared to the force laws found in molecular dynamics.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] As one of simplest examples, they define a force law where attraction dominates over long distances and repulsion dominates on short distances.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The force laws can be distinct between various robots.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] An individual robot's motion is controlled by the resultant artificial force imposed by other robots and other components of the system.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The Social Potential Fields approach is distributed since the force calculations and motion control can be done in an asynchronous and distributed manner.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Using specially tailored force laws, they demonstrate complex behaviors and what might be viewed as "social relations' among robots.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Therefore, the model was termed "Social Potential Fields”.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] They demonstrated by computer simulations that the method can yield interesting and useful behaviors among robots, including clustering, guarding, escorting, patrolling, etc.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The 1999 paper envisioned many industrial and military applications such as assembling, transporting, hazardous inspection. patrolling, and military control of swarm systems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Their simulations showed the social potential fields method is robust in that the method can tolerate errors in sensors and actuators.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The Social Potential Fields paper also extended the social potential fields model to use spring laws as force laws.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Evolutionary algorithms (EA), particle swarm optimization (PSO), differential evolution (DE), ant colony optimization (ACO) and their variants dominate the field of nature-inspired metaheuristics.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] This list includes algorithms published up to circa the year 2000.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] A large number of more recent metaphor-inspired metaheuristics have started to attract criticism in the research community for hiding their lack of novelty behind an elaborate metaphor.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] For algorithms published since that time, see List of metaphor-based metaheuristics.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Popular modern post-2000 examples include Grey Wolf Optimization (GWO), which replicates the dynamic hunting mechanisms and social leadership hierarchies of wolves in nature.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Metaheuristics lack a confidence in a solution.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] When appropriate parameters are determined, and when sufficient convergence stage is achieved, they often find a solution that is optimal, or near close to optimum – nevertheless, if one does not know optimal solution in advance, a quality of a solution is not known.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] In spite of this obvious drawback it has been shown that these types of algorithms work well in practice, and have been extensively researched, and developed.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] One such instance is Ant-inspired Monte Carlo algorithm for Minimum Feedback Arc Set where this has been achieved probabilistically via hybridization of Monte Carlo algorithm with Ant Colony Optimization technique.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Ant colony optimization (ACO), introduced by Dorigo in his doctoral dissertation, is a class of optimization algorithms modeled on the actions of an ant colony.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] ACO is a probabilistic technique useful in problems that deal with finding better paths through graphs.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Artificial 'ants'—simulation agents—locate optimal solutions by moving through a parameter space representing all possible solutions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Natural ants lay down pheromones directing each other to resources while exploring their environment.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The simulated 'ants' similarly record their positions and the quality of their solutions, so that in later simulation iterations more ants locate for better solutions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Particle swarm optimization (PSO) is a global optimization algorithm for dealing with problems in which a best solution can be represented as a point or surface in an n-dimensional space.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Hypotheses are plotted in this space and seeded with an initial velocity, as well as a communication channel between the particles.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Particles then move through the solution space, and are evaluated according to some fitness criterion after each timestep.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Over time, particles are accelerated towards those particles within their communication grouping which have better fitness values.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The main advantage of such an approach over other global minimization strategies such as simulated annealing is that the large number of members that make up the particle swarm make the technique impressively resilient to the problem of local minima.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Artificial Swarm Intelligence (ASI) is method of amplifying the collective intelligence of networked human groups using control algorithms modeled after natural swarms.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] ASI has also been used to enable groups of doctors to generate diagnoses with significantly higher accuracy than traditional methods.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] ASI has been used by the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) of the United Nations to help forecast famines in hotspots around the world.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Swarm Intelligence-based techniques can be used in a number of applications.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The U.S. military is investigating swarm techniques for controlling unmanned vehicles.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The European Space Agency is thinking about an orbital swarm for self-assembly and interferometry.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] NASA is investigating the use of swarm technology for planetary mapping.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Bekey discusses the possibility of using swarm intelligence to control nanobots within the body for the purpose of killing cancer tumors.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Conversely al-Rifaie and Aber have used stochastic diffusion search to help locate tumours.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence (SI) is increasingly applied in Internet of Things (IoT) systems, and by association to Intent-Based Networking (IBN), due to its ability to handle complex, distributed tasks through decentralized, self-organizing algorithms.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence has also been applied for data mining and cluster analysis.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Ant-based models are further subject of modern management theory.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence can be used in many practical areas where multiple simple agents work together to solve complex problems efficiently.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] It is commonly applied in optimization problems, such as route planning, scheduling, and resource allocation, where algorithms inspired by ants and birds help find the best solutions.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] In robotics, swarm intelligence is used for coordinating multiple robots in tasks like search and rescue, warehouse automation, and environmental monitoring.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] It is also widely used in network systems for efficient routing of data in the internet and wireless sensor networks.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] In addition, swarm intelligence plays an important role in traffic and transportation systems, where it helps in traffic signal control, vehicle routing, and reducing congestion in smart cities.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] In machine learning and data mining, it is used for feature selection, clustering, and improving model performance.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] It is also applied in power systems for load balancing and energy optimization, especially in smart grids.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Furthermore, swarm intelligence is used in healthcare and bioinformatics for tasks like drug discovery and gene analysis, and in gaming and simulations to create realistic group behaviors such as crowd movement or flocking.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The use of swarm intelligence in telecommunication networks has also been researched, in the form of ant-based routing.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] This was pioneered separately by Dorigo et al. and Hewlett-Packard in the mid-1990s, with a number of variants existing.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Basically, this uses a probabilistic routing table rewarding/reinforcing the route successfully traversed by each "ant" (a small control packet) which flood the network.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] As the system behaves stochastically and is therefore lacking repeatability, there are large hurdles to commercial deployment.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Mobile media and new technologies have the potential to change the threshold for collective action due to swarm intelligence (Rheingold: 2002, P175).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The location of transmission infrastructure for wireless communication networks is an important engineering problem involving competing objectives.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] A minimal selection of locations (or sites) are required subject to providing adequate area coverage for users.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] A very different, ant-inspired swarm intelligence algorithm, stochastic diffusion search (SDS), has been successfully used to provide a general model for this problem, related to circle packing and set covering.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] It has been shown that the SDS can be applied to identify suitable solutions even for large problem instances.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Airlines have also used ant-based routing in assigning aircraft arrivals to airport gates.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] At Southwest Airlines a software program uses swarm theory, or swarm intelligence—the idea that a colony of ants works better than one alone.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Each pilot acts like an ant searching for the best airport gate.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] "The pilot learns from his experience what's the best for him, and it turns out that that's the best solution for the airline," Douglas A.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] As a result, the "colony" of pilots always go to gates they can arrive at and depart from quickly.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The program can even alert a pilot of plane back-ups before they happen.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] "We can anticipate that it's going to happen, so we'll have a gate available," Lawson says.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Artists are using swarm technology as a means of creating complex interactive systems or simulating crowds.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Tim Burton's *Batman Returns* also made use of swarm technology for showing the movements of a group of bats.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Airlines have used swarm theory to simulate passengers boarding a plane.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Southwest Airlines researcher Douglas A.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Lawson used an ant-based computer simulation employing only six interaction rules to evaluate boarding times using various boarding methods.(Miller, 2010, xii-xviii).
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Networks of distributed users can be organized into "human swarms" through the implementation of real-time closed-loop control systems.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Developed by Louis Rosenberg in 2015, human swarming, also called artificial swarm intelligence, allows the collective intelligence of interconnected groups of people online to be harnessed.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The collective intelligence of the group often exceeds the abilities of any one member of the group.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] In one such study, swarms of human radiologists connected together were tasked with diagnosing chest x-rays and demonstrated a 33% reduction in diagnostic errors as compared to the traditional human methods, and a 22% improvement over traditional machine-learning.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The University of California San Francisco (UCSF) School of Medicine released a preprint in 2021 about the diagnosis of MRI images by small groups of collaborating doctors.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The study showed a 23% increase in diagnostic accuracy when using Artificial Swarm Intelligence (ASI) technology compared to majority voting.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Swarm grammars are swarms of stochastic grammars that can be evolved to describe complex properties such as found in art and architecture.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] These grammars interact as agents behaving according to rules of swarm intelligence.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Such behavior can also suggest deep learning algorithms, in particular when mapping of such swarms to neural circuits is considered.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The "creativity" of this hybrid swarm system has been analysed under the philosophical light of the "rhizome" in the context of Deleuze's "Orchid and Wasp" metaphor.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] A more recent work of al-Rifaie et al., "Swarmic Sketches and Attention Mechanism", introduces a novel approach deploying the mechanism of 'attention' by adapting SDS to selectively attend to detailed areas of a digital canvas.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Once the attention of the swarm is drawn to a certain line within the canvas, the capability of PSO is used to produce a 'swarmic sketch' of the attended line.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The swarms move throughout the digital canvas in an attempt to satisfy their dynamic roles—attention to areas with more details—associated with them via their fitness function.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Having associated the rendering process with the concepts of attention, the performance of the participating swarms creates a unique, non-identical sketch each time the 'artist' swarms embark on interpreting the input line drawings.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] In other works, while PSO is responsible for the sketching process, SDS controls the attention of the swarm.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] In a similar work, "Swarmic Paintings and Colour Attention", non-photorealistic images are produced using SDS algorithm which, in the context of this work, is responsible for colour attention.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] The "computational creativity" of the above-mentioned systems are discussed in through the two prerequisites of creativity (i.e. freedom and constraints) within the swarm intelligence's two infamous phases of exploration and exploitation.
[src:multi-agent-systems-ai/swarm-intelligence] Michael Theodore and Nikolaus Correll use swarm intelligent art installation to explore what it takes to have engineered systems to appear lifelike.
